# Binding project flows (non-negotiable)

These rules override convenience. Do **not** invent alternate workflows, skip steps, or argue that docs are optional.

## Authority order

1. Deterministic **Cursor hooks** + **git hooks** (cannot be ignored)
2. Always-on Cursor rules (this file + `generic-core` + `generic-cleanliness`)
3. [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) and [docs/](docs/INDEX.md)

If a hook or rule conflicts with a shorter path, **follow the hook/rule**.

## MUST

1. Read [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) at session start before implementing
2. **Branch first** — create `feature/...` or `fix/...` from `main` before any implementation commits
3. Use Conventional Commits only
4. Let git hooks run `scripts/validate.sh` (same as CI) — never ask the user to “just push”
5. Update `CHANGELOG.md` `[Unreleased]` for behaviour changes; register new docs in `docs/INDEX.md`
6. Prefer libraries; keep separation of responsibilities; follow [docs/cleanliness-and-organization.md](docs/cleanliness-and-organization.md)
7. English only in repository files

## NEVER

1. Commit or push while on `main` (except when the user explicitly orders a release-merge they will do themselves)
2. Pass `--no-verify`, `--no-gpg-sign`, or otherwise skip hooks
3. `git push --force` / `--force-with-lease` to `main`
4. Hand-bump SemVer in normal flow (release-please owns releases)
5. Commit secrets or `.env`
6. Dump orphan files at repo root or invent parallel folder layouts

## When stuck

Do not weaken the flow. Ask the user, or stop and report the blocker.
